  that element measured in grams."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.515453Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9660-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Heating magnesium in a crucible will react it with oxygen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.515556Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9660-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The crucible must be opened periodically to ensure enough oxygen enters the vessel
  to completely oxidise the magnesium."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.515560Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9660-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Opening the crucible too much will cause mass/product loss."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.515564Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9660-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Safety precautions should be taken when burning magnesium because of the bright
  light produced."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.515571Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9660-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The stoichiometry for a reaction can be calculated given experimental data."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.515576Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9639-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A mixture consists of two or more elements and/or compounds, not chemically combined
  together."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.516255Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9639-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Chemical properties of each substance in a mixture remain unchanged."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.516259Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9639-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are multiple physical processes for separating mixtures."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.516264Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9639-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Melting point data can be used to distinguish between pure substances and
  mixtures."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.516268Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9639-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A formulation is a designed mixture, with each component serving a specific
  purpose."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.516273Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8329-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Atoms are the building blocks that can be combined in different ways to form
  different substances."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.518858Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8329-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is impossible for any atom to be changed into a different type of atom by a
  chemical reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.518863Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8329-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All of the atoms in the reactants of a chemical reaction are reorganised to form all
  of the products of the reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.518867Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8329-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is impossible to make a particular product without all the atoms that it
  needs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.518872Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8329-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The law of conservation of mass can be applied to a closed system, or a non-enclosed
  system that takes in/gives out gas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.518876Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8330-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a chemical reaction the + symbol can be read as ‘and’ and the arrow as ‘changes
  into’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.533397Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8330-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In an oxidation reaction a reactant combines with oxygen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.533401Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8330-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In a decomposition reaction a reactant splits into two or more new substances."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.533406Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8330-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In a precipitation reaction an insoluble salt is formed."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.533410Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27912-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Unique tests for each substance help minimise errors and ensure correct
  identification."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.535988Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27912-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Gas tests can be used to identify carbon dioxide, oxygen, hydrogen and ammonia."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.535993Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27912-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Observations and results should be recorded accurately for analysis during the
  practical."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.535997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27912-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Flow charts break down complex activities into ordered sets of simpler steps,
  crucial for efficient ion identification."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.536002Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8328-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Unique tests for each substance help minimise errors and ensure correct
  identification."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.536094Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8328-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Flow charts break down complex activities into ordered sets of simpler steps,
  crucial for efficient ion identification."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.536101Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8328-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Observations and results should be recorded accurately for analysis during the
  practical."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.536106Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20359-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Heating magnesium in a crucible will react it with oxygen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.536183Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20359-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The crucible must be opened periodically to ensure enough oxygen enters the vessel
  to completely oxidise the magnesium."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.536187Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20359-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Opening the crucible too much will cause mass/product loss."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.536192Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20359-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Safety precautions should be taken when burning magnesium because of the bright
  light produced."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.536196Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20359-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The stoichiometry for a reaction can be calculated given experimental data."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.536201Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8325-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some metal ions form coloured precipitates in a reaction with sodium hydroxide
  solution."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.545762Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8325-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ammonium ions can be identified by heating with NaOH and using damp red litmus
  paper, which turns blue if positive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.545767Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8325-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A dilute acid is usually added before testing for carbonates, sulfates or halides to
  avoid false positives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.545773Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8325-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Halide ions produce different coloured precipitates when silver nitrate is added to
  a solution containing them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.545781Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8325-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A white precipitate is formed when barium chloride is added to an acidified solution
  containing sulfate ions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.545789Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9748-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The uses of polymers are related to their properties."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.548180Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9748-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are many problems associated with polymers (e.g. availability of raw
  materials, landfill, combustion)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.548184Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9748-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are many advantages and disadvantages to recycling polymers (e.g. economical
  and environmental)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.548189Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9747-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A chemical test can identify the differences between alkanes and alkenes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.548193Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9747-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Data from calorimetry and viscosity experiments can be used to predict the chain
  length of alkanes, alkenes & alcohols."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.548198Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9747-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "As chain length increases, more energy is released during combustion."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.548202Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9747-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """As chain length increases, the viscosity of alkanes, alkenes and alcohols
  increases."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.548206Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8428-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alcohols can react, at their functional group -OH, with sodium, oxygen, water, or an
  oxidising agent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.548763Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8428-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Alcohols need less oxygen than equivalent alkanes in order to burn completely."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.548771Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8428-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Alcohols are good solvents which also mix with water."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.548776Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8428-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The boiling point of ethanol is much higher than the boiling point of ethane."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.548782Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8428-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ethanol can be formed via fermentation of glucose (renewable) or via hydration of
  ethene (non-renewable)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.548787Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8427-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Reactions of an alkene happen at its functional group, C=C."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.552334Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8427-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Reactions of an alkene change it from an unsaturated to a saturated molecule."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.552338Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8427-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Larger alkenes have higher boiling points and are less flammable."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.552342Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8427-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Alkenes tend to burn with smoky flames due to incomplete combustion."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.552347Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8427-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Isomers are structures with the same molecular formula, but different arrangement of
  atoms in space."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.552351Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8429-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Carboxylic acids have a -COOH functional group."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.555367Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8429-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Carboxylic acids are weak acids."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.555371Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8429-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "When ethanol is oxidised, ethanoic acid is formed."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.555375Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8429-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carboxylic acids react with carbonates to produce a metal salt, carbon dioxide and
  water."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.555380Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8429-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carboxylic acid can react with alcohol to produce esters (such as ethyl
  ethanoate)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.555384Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8430-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A polymer is a substance of high average relative molecular mass made up of small
  repeating units."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.555388Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8430-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In addition polymerisation only one molecule is formed, e.g. addition polymerisation
  of ethene forms poly(ethene)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.555392Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8430-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Polymers have a specific displayed formula to show repeat units."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.555399Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8430-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A polymer's monomer can be deduced from its structure and vice versa."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.555403Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8430-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Addition polymers can be made by combining together a variety of monomer molecules
  containing C=C."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.555407Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8431-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Condensation polymerisation requires monomers with two functional groups."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.566789Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8431-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Condensation polymers can be made of two different monomers."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.566793Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8431-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A polyester is formed by reaction of a monomer with two carboxylic acid groups with
  a monomer with two alcohol groups."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.566798Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8431-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In condensation polymerisation as well as the polymer a small molecule is formed,
  usually water."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.566802Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8431-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Amino acids contain two functional groups and can form polypeptides and
  proteins."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.566806Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9627-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Dot and cross diagrams as a model for binary ionic substances"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.570950Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9627-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Dot and cross diagrams show the empirical formula/ratio of atoms to show how
  electrons are transferred"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.570954Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9627-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ions are shown with full outer shells, square brackets, and a charge in the top
  right corner."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.570959Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9627-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ionic compounds are neutral overall, so positive and negative charge must
  balance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.570963Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9627-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When positive ions do not have the same magnitude of charge as negative ions,
  multiple of some ions will be required."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.570967Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9682-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Molecular modelling represents the bonding and structure of substances."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.571157Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9682-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The way giant covalent structures melt/boil is very different to simple
  molecules."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.571161Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9682-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Diamond is very hard, has a very high melting point and does not conduct
  electricity, every atom is bonded to another."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.571167Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9682-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In graphite each atom is bonded to three others to form layers of hexagonal rings.
  Each atom contributes a free electron"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.571174Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9682-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Simple molecules are held together by intermolecular forces, no chemical bonds hold
  them together."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.571178Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20687-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are five different types of substance: monatomic, simple covalent (molecules),
  giant covalent, ionic and metallic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.572186Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20687-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The outer shell in most atoms can hold 8 electrons but, in hydrogen and helium, it
  can only hold 2 electrons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.572191Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20687-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Most atoms increase their stability by forming bonds with other atoms so that they
  have a full outer shell of electrons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.572195Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20687-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Some atoms will share electrons with other atoms to increase their stability."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.572199Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20687-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some atoms will lose or gain electrons to increase stability forming cations or
  anions, respectfully."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.572204Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9689-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In all chemical reactions, bonds in the reactants need to be broken before the
  reaction can happen"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.573906Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9689-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Energy must be supplied to break bonds in the reactants"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.573910Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9689-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Energy is released when bonds in the products are formed"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.573915Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9689-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The difference between the energy needed to break bonds and the energy released is
  the overall energy change"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.573919Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9680-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carbon atoms will form up to four covalent bonds (as they will fill their outer
  shell with four more electrons)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.573923Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9680-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carbon atoms can combine with other non-metal atoms to make a wide range of
  molecules, some with chains and rings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.573927Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9680-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "An organic compound contains two or more elements (including carbon)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.573932Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9680-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A lot of organic compounds also include hydrogen, oxygen and nitrogen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.573936Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9680-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Organic compounds can be found both in nature, but also produced synthetically."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.573940Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9692-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Polymers are very large covalent molecules (not giant structures)"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575113Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9692-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Polymers can be represented by showing repeated units"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575117Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9692-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Polymers consist of repeating and identical sections called monomers"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575121Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9692-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Polymers are solid at room temperature because the intermolecular forces between
  polymer molecules are relatively strong"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575125Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8409-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Catalysts, pressure, temperature & concentration of solutions can affect equilibrium
  position of a reversible reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575129Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8409-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the conditions of a reversible reaction are changed, the equilibrium will move to
  counteract that change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575134Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8409-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A catalyst increases the rate at which equilibrium is achieved."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575138Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8409-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Increasing temperature increases the rate of both reactions; equilibrium shifts in
  favour of the endothermic reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575144Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8409-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Increasing the concentration or pressure of a substance increases the rate of
  reaction; equilibrium shifts in response."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575151Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9623-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The periodic table is ordered by increasing atomic number (proton number)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575200Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9623-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The periodic table is split into periods and groups."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575204Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9623-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The position of an element in the periodic table is linked to its atomic number and
  the arrangement of its electrons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575208Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9623-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Elements can be classed as metals or non-metals according to their position on the
  periodic table."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575212Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9623-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A useful model for atoms arranges electrons in shells around the nucleus."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.575216Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9670-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Concentration of an aqueous solution is the mass of solute dissolved in 1 dm³ of
  distilled water, in g/dm³."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.578256Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9670-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mass of one mole of solute is equal to the relative mass of the solute measured
  in grams."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.578261Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9670-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Concentration can be expressed in g/dm³ or mol/dm³."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.578265Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9670-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Equal volumes of solutions of the same concentration (in mol/dm³) have equal numbers
  of dissolved solute particles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.578269Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9670-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Volume can be measured in various units; 1 dm³ is equivalent to 1000 cm³."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.578273Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9724-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The ozone layer protects life from harmful ultraviolet (UV) radiation from
  the Sun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.578831Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9724-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) were once used, and when they entered our atmosphere
  reacted with ozone (O₃)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.578838Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9724-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ozone levels decreased, but scientific communication led to action being taken to
  prevent further loss of ozone."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.578842Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9724-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The work of analytical scientists suggests the ozone layer is now reforming."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.578849Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20425-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Calorimetry can be used to measure a reaction's energy change indirectly."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.581040Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20425-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Calorimetry data can be used to calculate the mass of alcohol needed to cause a 1°C
  rise in temperature of the water."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.581044Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20425-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An alcohol that causes a 1°C temperature rise when the least amount is combusted is
  releasing the most energy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.581048Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20425-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The energy change of combustion for a variety of alcohols can be compared to the
  molecular formula of each alcohol."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.581053Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20086-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The periodic table is ordered by increasing atomic number (proton number)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.582168Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20086-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The periodic table is split into periods and groups."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.582172Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20086-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The position of an element in the periodic table is linked to its atomic number and
  the arrangement of its electrons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.582179Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20086-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Elements can be classed as metals or non-metals according to their position on the
  periodic table."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.582183Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20086-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A useful model for atoms arranges electrons in shells around the nucleus."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.582189Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9624-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are five different types of substance: monatomic, simple covalent (molecules),
  giant covalent, ionic and metallic"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.587979Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9624-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The outer shell in most atoms can hold 8 electrons but, in hydrogen and helium, it
  can only hold 2 electrons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.587984Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9624-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Most atoms increase their stability by forming bonds with other atoms so that they
  have a full outer shell of electrons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.587988Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9624-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Some atoms will share electrons with other atoms to increase their stability."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.587992Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9624-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some atoms will lose or gain electrons to increase stability forming cations or
  anions, respectively."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.587996Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9745-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some metal ions form coloured precipitates in a reaction with sodium hydroxide
  solution."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.592832Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9745-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ammonium ions can be identified by heating with NaOH and using damp red litmus
  paper, which turns blue if positive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.592836Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9745-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A dilute acid is usually added before testing for carbonates, sulfates or halides to
  avoid false positives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.592840Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9745-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Halide ions produce different coloured precipitates when silver nitrate is added to
  a solution containing them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.592845Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9745-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A white precipitate is formed when barium chloride is added to an acidified solution
  containing sulfate ions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.592849Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9656-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All the atoms in the reactants of a chemical reaction are reorganised to form all
  the products of the reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.599643Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9656-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There must be an equal number of each type of atom on both the reactant and product
  side of the equation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.599647Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9656-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Chemical formulae cannot be altered to balance a reaction equation; only
  coefficients can change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.599651Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9656-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Atoms cannot be created or destroyed. During a chemical reaction, atoms are simply
  rearranged into products."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.599656Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8313-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The atomic model has changed over time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.600896Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8313-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Dalton, Thomson, Rutherford (Geiger and Marsden), Bohr and Chadwick have all
  suggested atomic models."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.600900Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8313-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The plum pudding model of the atom and the nuclear model are two important models in
  the history of the atom's discovery"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.600905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8313-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "New evidence from the scattering experiment led to a change in the atomic model."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.600909Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8378-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The changing rate of a chemical reaction can be represented by a graph of volume of
  gas produced against time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.602383Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8378-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When reacting excess acid, the same volume of gas is produced for equal amounts of
  magnesium."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.602387Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8378-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Doubling the concentration doubles the rate of reaction."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.602392Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8378-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The gradient of a rate of reaction graph can be calculated from a tangent drawn at a
  point on the curve."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.602396Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8370-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Electric cells contain a store of chemicals that react to produce a voltage across
  two electrical contacts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.602443Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8370-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An electric cell made of two different metals in contact with an electrolyte,
  produces a voltage across the metals."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.602447Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8370-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The size of voltage across an electric cell depends on the materials it is made
  from."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.602452Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8370-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A battery is made of one or more electric cells, which can be connected in series to
  produce a larger voltage."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.602456Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8370-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The chemical reaction in a rechargeable battery is reversed when an external voltage
  is connected across it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.602460Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8334-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a chemical reaction, the atoms in reactants are rearranged and are the same atoms
  that are in the products."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613224Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8334-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Chemical equations are most correctly interpreted in terms of molar ratios (i.e. 1
  mole of A reacts with 2 moles of B)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613228Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8334-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The molar ratios of the substances in a chemical reaction is known as stoichiometry,
  which means ‘measuring elements’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613232Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8334-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The stoichiometry of a reaction is shown by coefficients in a balanced equation.
  These molar relationships don't change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613237Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8334-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The moles of substance in a reaction can be determined using: mass(g) = Mr × moles
  (& the stoichiometry of reaction)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613241Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9685-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Hydrocarbons are simple covalent compounds made of hydrogen and carbon atoms
  only."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613245Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9685-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Hydrocarbons are found in crude oil, and are used as fuels and feedstock."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613250Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9685-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alkanes consist of chains, or rings, of carbon atoms that are each also bonded to
  hydrogen atoms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613254Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9685-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alkanes are a homologous series of hydrocarbons, with the same general formula with
  a trend in properties."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613261Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9685-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The general formula for an alkane is CnH2n+2."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613266Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8373-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Particles of reactants in a chemical reaction can react together if they collide
  with sufficient energy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613321Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8373-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Increasing surface area of a solid lets more reacting particles in a solution
  collide with its particles each second."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613325Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8373-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Increasing concentration of a reacting solution introduces more reactant particles,
  so they collide more frequently."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613329Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8373-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Increasing temperature of reactants increases the speed of particles, so they
  collide more frequently."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613334Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8373-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Increasing pressure of reacting gases pushes reactant particles closer together, so
  they collide more frequently."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.613338Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20081-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The atomic number of an element states the number of protons in the nucleus of every
  atom of that element."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.616060Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20081-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The number of electrons in an atom is equal to the number of protons in the nucleus
  of the atom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.616064Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20081-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mass number of an element is about equal to the number of protons and neutrons
  in atoms of that element."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.616068Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9664-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Whenever a measurement is made, there is always some uncertainty about the result
  obtained."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.617792Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9664-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The uncertainty of an individual measurement is equal to half the resolution of the
  device used to take the measurement."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.617799Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9664-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The higher the resolution, the lower the uncertainty of an individual
  measurement."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.617804Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9664-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Half the range of repeated measurements equals the uncertainty of a mean value."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.617808Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9664-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The uncertainty of a measurement provides a range within which the actual value can
  be found."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.617813Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20084-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The atomic model has changed over time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.634196Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20084-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Dalton, Thomson, Rutherford (Geiger and Marsden), Bohr and Chadwick have all
  suggested atomic models."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.634200Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20084-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The plum pudding model of the atom & the nuclear model are two important models in
  the history of the atom's discovery."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.634204Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20084-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "New evidence from the scattering experiment led to a change in the atomic model."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.634209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27388-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Transition metals are generally stronger, harder, more dense and have higher melting
  points than Group 1 metals."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.636396Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27388-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Transition metals react slowly with water or don’t react with it at all."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.636402Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27388-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Transition metals are often catalysts that speed up chemical reactions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.636406Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27388-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Transition metals can form ions with different charges and their compounds often
  exhibit vibrant colours."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.636411Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9693-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A more reactive element will replace a less reactive element in a compound
  (displacement)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.636415Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9693-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The more easily a metal atom forms a positive ion, the more reactive it is."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.636419Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9693-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Some metals react with acid to produce a metal salt and hydrogen gas."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.636426Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9693-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Some metals react with water to produce a metal hydroxide and hydrogen gas."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.636432Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9693-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carbon is a non-metal element often included in the reactivity series between
  aluminium and zinc."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.636436Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9755-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A half–equation describes what happens to one reactant in a reaction, such as the
  process at an individual electrode."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637828Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9755-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Half–equations show balanced charges as well as balanced atoms."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637832Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9755-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A balanced ionic equation shows all reacting ions involved in a reaction."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637837Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9755-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Ions not involved in a reaction do not appear in a balanced ionic equation."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637841Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9694-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Oxidation is the loss of electrons and reduction is the gain of electrons."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637845Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9694-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Half equations can be written to show which species are oxidised and which are
  reduced."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637849Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9694-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Ionic equations can be written for displacement reactions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637853Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8331-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The relative atomic mass is the mean mass of an atom compared to 1/12 of the mass of
  a carbon-12 atom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637875Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8331-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The relative formula mass (RFM or Mr) is the sum of the relative atomic masses of
  all the atoms in a chemical formula."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8331-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """%mass of an element in a compound = (relative mass of element in compound ÷ RFM of
  compound) × 100"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637883Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9659-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The stoichiometry of a chemical reaction is the molar ratio of each substance in a
  balanced symbol equation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637959Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9659-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Stoichiometric values can be calculated using masses found by experiment."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637963Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9659-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Subscript values in chemical formula indicate the ratio of atoms/ions in a
  molecule/formula unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.637970Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8347-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a covalent bond, two non-metal atoms share a pair of electrons (from their outer
  shells)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.638061Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8347-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """For every one electron needed to complete the outer shell of an atom, one covalent
  bond will form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.638066Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8347-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Atoms can share multiple pairs of electrons."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.638070Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8347-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Displayed formulae of covalent substances are a model, showing lines to represent
  shared pairs of electrons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.638074Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8402-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Carbon dioxide and methane are common greenhouse gases."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.638802Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8402-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Greenhouse gases reduce the amount of lower-energy IR that can escape from Earth’s
  atmosphere."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.638806Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8402-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Greenhouse gases do not reduce the amount of higher-energy IR radiation entering the
  atmosphere from the Sun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.638810Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8402-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the rate energy is transferred into the atmosphere exceeds the rate it is
  transferred out, average temperatures rise."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.638814Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8402-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An increasing average temperature of Earth’s atmosphere is called global
  warming."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.638818Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9631-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Scientists use models to represent parts of the natural world that are too difficult
  to observe or explain directly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.640870Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9631-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are multiple ways (models) of drawing/showing bonding."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.640874Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9631-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are multiple advantages and limitations of particular representations and
  models."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.640878Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20095-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Atoms of every element consist of the same three subatomic particles."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.640901Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20095-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All elements consist of their own atoms, with a unique number of protons defining
  the element."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.640905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20095-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Everything around us is made of different combinations of atoms, either on their
  own, or in compound form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.640909Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20095-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """We use element symbols in formulae as a common language to share chemical
  compositions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.640915Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8401-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The combustion of fossil fuels adds more carbon dioxide to the atmosphere."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.645760Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8401-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carbon dioxide added to the atmosphere in one place will, over time, spread
  throughout Earth’s atmosphere."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.645764Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8401-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Plants act as carbon sinks because, as they grow, they remove carbon dioxide from
  the atmosphere."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.645769Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8401-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The decomposition or combustion of plants returns the carbon they are storing into
  the atmosphere."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.645773Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8401-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Human activity is adding carbon dioxide to the atmosphere more quickly than it is
  being removed by natural processes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.645777Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9967-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Chromatograms can identify unknown substances by qualitative visual comparison or
  quantitatively by Rf value comparison."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.645851Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9967-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Appropriate equipment should be employed when using chromatograms to identify
  unknown substances in a mixture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.645855Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9967-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "An appropriate number of significant figures should be used in calculations."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.645859Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9946-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Electrons have a relative charge of -1 and roughly a relative mass of 0.0005 (very
  small)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.818306Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9946-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Protons are found in the atomic nucleus, have a relative electric charge of +1, and
  a relative mass of 1."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.818315Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9946-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Neutrons are found in the atomic nucleus, have no electric charge, and a relative
  mass of 1."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.818322Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9946-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An atom has no electric charge as it contains equal numbers of protons and electrons
  to balance the charge."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.818331Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9946-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The atom has a nucleus surrounded by electrons, with the nuclear radius much smaller
  than that of the atom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.818338Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8343-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Atoms are more stable when they have a full outer shell."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822423Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8343-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Metal atoms become more stable when they lose the electron(s) in their outer shell,
  and become positive ions (cations)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8343-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Non–metal atoms become more stable when they gain electrons to fill their outer
  shell and become negative ions (anions)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822438Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8343-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Ions form through the loss or gain of electrons."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822446Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8343-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Standard ion notation uses superscript charge values where the charge follows the
  number (e.g. 2+, not +2)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822453Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20686-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Atoms are more stable when they have a full outer shell."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822776Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20686-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Metal atoms become more stable when they lose the electron(s) in their outer shell,
  and become positive ions (cations)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822783Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20686-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Non–metal atoms become more stable when they gain electrons to fill their outer
  shell and become negative ions (anions)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822790Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20686-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Ions form through the loss or gain of electrons."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822798Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20686-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Standard ion notation uses superscript charge values where the charge follows the
  number (e.g. 2+, not +2)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822809Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9619-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Electrons have a relative charge of -1 and roughly a relative mass of 0.0005."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822943Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9619-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Protons are found in the atomic nucleus, have a relative electric charge of +1, and
  a relative mass of 1."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822950Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9619-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Neutrons are found in the atomic nucleus, have no electric charge, and a relative
  mass of 1."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822957Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9619-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An atom has no electric charge and contains equal numbers of protons and electrons
  to balance the charge."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822964Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9619-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The atom has a nucleus surrounded by electrons, with the nuclear radius much smaller
  than that of the atom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.822972Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8403-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Increasing average global temperatures leads to an increase in sea levels."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823292Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8403-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Increasing average temperatures cause more powerful convection currents, increasing
  the number and severity of storms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823299Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8403-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Increasing average temperatures can affect atmospheric air streams and change
  weather patterns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823317Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8403-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Changes of human behaviour can lead to smaller increases in global temperature."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823325Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8403-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Climate engineering may enable humans to reduce global temperatures through the
  application of technologies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823333Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8371-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Most chemical reactions start more quickly and slow down as they progress."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823340Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8371-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The rate of a chemical reaction is equal to the amount of product formed per unit
  time (or reactant used per unit time)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823347Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8371-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mean rate of a chemical reaction is different to the instantaneous rate that
  changes throughout the reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823355Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8371-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Graphs of mass, volume, or concentration vs. time can all represent the changing
  rate of a chemical reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823362Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8371-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The gradient of a rate of reaction graph can be calculated from a tangent drawn at a
  point on the curve."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823369Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8369-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fractions of crude oil have different properties and uses, affecting the demand for
  these molecules."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823410Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8369-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Larger hydrocarbons can be broken down (cracked) to produce smaller, more useful
  molecules."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823417Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8369-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cracking can be done by various methods including catalytic cracking and steam
  cracking."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823425Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8369-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The products of cracking include alkanes and alkenes, which have a double bond
  between two carbon atoms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823436Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8369-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Bromine water changes from orange/brown to colourless in the presence of an
  alkene."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823444Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9634-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A simple particle model explains melting, boiling, freezing, and condensing
  processes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823451Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9634-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Boiling is when a liquid becomes a gas throughout, forming bubbles. Condensation is
  when gas turns into liquid."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823459Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9634-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Melting is when a solid turns into a liquid with added energy. Freezing is the
  reverse: liquid to solid, losing energy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823466Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9634-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The particles remain the same size and shape as they do not have bulk properties
  like melting and boiling points."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823473Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9754-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Purification of copper involves using copper electrodes in an electrolyte."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823481Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9754-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The electrolyte must contain the same ions, in solution, as the metal being purified
  by electrolysis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823488Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9754-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Measuring the mass change in the copper electrodes demonstrates the transfer of
  copper."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823500Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9754-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Impurities in the anode do not transfer to the cathode, leading to pure copper
  deposition."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823507Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9754-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Other uses for this technique include electroplating, where you would use multiple
  metals e.g. gold."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823514Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9640-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A solution is a type of mixture made of a solvent and a solute."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823522Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9640-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Solutions form due to a solute dissolving in the solvent."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823530Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9640-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Solubility is a measure of how well a chemical dissolves (soluble/insoluble)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823537Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9640-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Many substances can act as a solvent; however, water is the most common."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823544Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9640-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """State symbols are used to identify the three states of matter and aqueous solutions
  in chemical equations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823552Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9679-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Data collected during a titration allows chemists to determine a solution’s unknown
  concentration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823559Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9679-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Concordant titres should be used when calculating a mean volume used to neutralise a
  solution."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823570Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9679-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The coefficients in a balanced equation indicates the stoichiometry (i.e. molar
  ratio) between substances in a reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823581Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9679-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The concentration of an unknown solution is found using the relationship:
  concentration = moles ÷ volume (in dm³)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823589Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9715-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Scientists discovered and isolated fullerenes accidentally, which led to exciting
  new possibilities in chemistry."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823596Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9715-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Research into the allotropes of carbon is an important part of chemistry's history,
  earning multiple Nobel Prizes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823604Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9715-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Graphene is so thin that it's nearly transparent, allowing most light to pass
  through."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823611Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9715-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fullerenes, nanotubes, and graphene have a wide range of real-world uses in fields
  like electronics and medicine."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823619Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9715-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Scientific discoveries have the power to change the world, even if their
  significance takes time to be fully understood."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.823626Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20362-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a chemical reaction, the atoms in reactants are rearranged and are the same atoms
  that are in the products."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824742Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20362-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mass of products in a chemical reaction is equal to the mass of the
  reactants."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824749Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20362-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The sum of the RFM of the reactants equals the sum of the RFM of the products,
  taking account of balancing coefficients."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824756Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8351-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A salt is formed when an acid neutralises a base."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8351-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Salts are giant, 3D ionic structures that form crystals with regular arrangements of
  ions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824777Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8351-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The empirical chemical formula of a salt provides the ratio of metal to non-metal
  ions it contains."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824785Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8351-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Acids contain aqueous hydrogen ions, H⁺(aq) and alkalis contain aqueous hydroxide
  ions, OH⁻(aq)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824792Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8351-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "During a neutralisation reaction: H⁺(aq) + OH⁻(aq) → H₂O(l)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824799Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8348-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Typical atomic radii, and bond length, are in the order of 10⁻¹⁰m."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824806Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8348-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Non-metal elements and non-metal compounds form covalent structures."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824812Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8348-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Simple covalent substances have no free moving charge carriers so cannot conduct
  electricity (some giant covalent can)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824819Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8348-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Small molecules are usually gases or liquids with relatively low melting and boiling
  points."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824826Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8348-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Giant covalent structures have high melting/boiling points because strong covalent
  bonds need to be broken."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824834Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9722-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There is a correlation between increasing amounts of atmospheric carbon dioxide and
  a rising average global temperature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824841Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9722-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Increases in atmospheric carbon dioxide have been caused by human activity."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824847Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9722-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Overwhelming evidence shows human activity is responsible for the rapid global
  warming of the last 200 years."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824854Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9722-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Global warming measurements and conclusions are reliable despite some unavoidable
  uncertainty in measured values."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824861Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9722-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carbon footprints measure the annual greenhouse gas emissions of individuals,
  industry and nations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824872Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27390-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Corrosion is a general process of degradation of metals through various causes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27390-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Rusting is a specific type of corrosion, affecting iron in the presence of air and
  moisture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824886Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27390-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A metal oxide layer can protect the underlying metal if the oxide forms a physical
  barrier."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824897Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27390-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some coatings are reactive and contain a more reactive metal to provide sacrificial
  protection, e.g. zinc to galvanise."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824908Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27390-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Electroplating can be used to improve the appearance and/or the resistance to
  corrosion of metal objects."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824915Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9675-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A chemical equation is used to represent the chemical reaction that occurs during
  the formation of a compound."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824922Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9675-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ionic equations can be used to show only the chemical species that are changing
  within a reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824929Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9675-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """State symbols (s), (l), (g) and (aq), are used in ionic equations to show which
  substances change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824936Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9675-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The ionic equation for water formation (neutralisation) is H⁺(aq) + OH⁻(aq) →
  H2O(l)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.824943Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8366-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Crude oil is a non-renewable mixture of different hydrocarbons and impurities."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.825089Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8366-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Crude oil can be separated into groups of hydrocarbon molecules of similar size,
  called fractions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.825096Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8366-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Most of the hydrocarbon molecules in crude oil are alkanes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.825102Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8366-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Smaller hydrocarbon molecules have lower boiling points, are more flammable, and are
  less viscous."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.825113Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8366-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fractions of crude oil include petroleum gases, petrol, kerosene, diesel oil, heavy
  fuel oil, and bitumen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.825120Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8424-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Industrial equilibria involve a trade-off between production rate and equilibrium
  position."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.825912Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8424-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Temperature, pressure, surface area, concentration, and catalysts impact rates and
  equilibrium, often in opposing ways."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.825919Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8424-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """High pressures and temperatures boost reaction rates but must balance safety and
  cost."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.825926Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8424-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "High pressures are costly and increase equipment failure risk."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.825933Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8424-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Low temperatures slow reactions but can favour desired product in exothermic
  reactions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.825940Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9633-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are three states of matter: solid state, liquid state, and gas state."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826565Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9633-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A substance in the gas state can be compressed because there is empty space between
  the particles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826575Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9633-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A substance in the liquid or solid state cannot be compressed because the particles
  are already touching."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826582Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9633-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A substance in the gas or liquid state has no fixed shape as the particles can move
  past each other."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826592Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9633-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A substance in the solid state will not flow because the particles vibrate in a
  fixed position."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826599Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9648-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fractional distillation is an extension of simple distillation, and is mostly used
  to separate mixtures of liquids."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826606Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9648-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A main distinction between fractional and simple distillation is that the former
  uses a fractionating column."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826613Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9648-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fractional distillation has multiple real-world examples, including the fractional
  distillation of air."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826619Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9648-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fractional distillation produces fractions; these can be pure or mixtures of
  chemicals with very similar boiling points."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826629Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8439-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A solid ionic compound cannot conduct electricity."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826669Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8439-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Salts are ionic compounds which can be electrolysed when they are in the molten
  state."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826676Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8439-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Gases may be formed at the electrodes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826683Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8439-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Freely moving ions can reach the electrodes and undergo oxidation or reduction."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826689Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8439-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A non-metal always forms at the positive electrode, and a metal forms at the
  negative electrode."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826696Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8393-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In phytoextraction, metal is extracted from a crop of plants that absorb metal ions
  through their roots."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826706Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8393-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In bioleaching, metal is extracted from bacteria that extract metal from an ore."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826713Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8393-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Electrolysis is a process used to separate metals from their compounds."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826719Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8393-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are advantages and disadvantages associated with each method of extracting
  metals."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826726Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-22197-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Contact Process involves the production of sulfur trioxide (SO₃) from sulfur
  dioxide (SO₂) using a catalyst."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826770Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-22197-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The process has three main stages: burning sulfur to produce SO₂, converting SO₂ to
  SO₃, then converting SO₃ to H₂SO₄."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826776Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-22197-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The conversion of SO₂ to SO₃ is a reversible reaction performed at 1-2 atmospheres
  and 450°C, using a V₂O₅ catalyst."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826783Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-22197-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Sulfuric acid production is energy-intensive and releases large amounts of CO₂,
  contributing to global emissions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826790Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-22197-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Sulfuric acid is vital for various industries, such as: fertilisers, chemical
  manufacturing, and petroleum refining."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826796Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9649-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Potable' and 'pure' water are not the same substance."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826803Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9649-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Water used in analysis must not contain any dissolved ions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826809Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9649-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The method used to obtain potable water depends on the water source."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826819Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9649-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Sedimentation, filtration and chlorination are used to obtain potable water from
  groundwater and fresh water sources."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826826Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9649-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Desalination of seawater creates potable water by distillation or reverse
  osmosis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826836Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9710-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Reduction is the gain of electrons, and oxidation is the loss of electrons."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826846Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9710-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Displacement reactions are often examples of redox reactions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826853Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9710-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Half equations show which elements are oxidised, and which are reduced."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826860Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8432-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "DNA is made from monomers called nucleotides."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826867Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8432-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Natural polymers are important for life."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826873Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8432-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The carbohydrates starch and cellulose are made from the monomer glucose."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826880Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8432-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Amino acids contain two functional groups and can form polypeptides and
  proteins."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826886Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8342-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Salts form ionic structures because they contain metal and non-metal ions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826893Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8342-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In an ionic structure each positive ion attracts the negative ions and
  vice-versa."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826899Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8342-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Metal ions attract all non-metal ions and vice-versa, they bond to the opposite
  charged ions that are closest."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826906Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8342-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An ionic bond is the electrostatic force of attraction between oppositely-charged
  ions acting in all directions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826912Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8342-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ionic substances are 3D lattices with regular arrangements of ions ( in a repeating
  pattern of +ve and -ve charge)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.826919Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8399-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Carbon monoxide gas is toxic."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827132Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8399-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Carbon particulates contribute to health issues and global dimming."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827138Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8399-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides are formed through burning fuels, and form acids
  in water."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827145Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8399-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Catalytic converters help complete combustion reactions and the removal of nitrogen
  monoxide from exhaust gases."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827151Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8399-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Hydrogen can be used as a fuel in cars and this has advantages and
  disadvantages."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827158Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9669-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Concentration of a solution is the mass of solute dissolved in 1 dm³ of distilled
  water, in g/dm³."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827296Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9669-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The more solute that is dissolved, the more concentrated the solution."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827302Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9669-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Solutions can be diluted (i.e. made less concentrated) by increasing the volume of
  distilled water."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827309Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9669-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Diluting solutions with distilled water ensures no other substances are present in
  the solution."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827316Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9669-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Volume can be measured in various units; 1 dm³ is equivalent to 1000 cm³."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827322Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8392-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Unreactive metals are often found in the earth as pure metal."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827508Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8392-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Metals that are less reactive than carbon can be extracted by heating their oxides
  with carbon."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827515Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8392-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A metal oxide is said to be reduced by carbon because the metal oxide loses
  oxygen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827521Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8392-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carbon is oxidised when it reacts with a metal oxide because it gains oxygen to form
  carbon dioxide."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.827528Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8380-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Measuring volume of gas produced throughout a reaction allows the changing rate of
  reaction to be calculated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828468Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8380-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Errors in measuring volumes of gas over time include timing, reading volumes in real
  time and gas displaced by the bung."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828475Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8380-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Measuring an end-point in a reaction allows direct and simple comparison of reaction
  rates."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828484Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8380-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Errors in measuring end-points include subjectivity of observations, measuring times
  and volumes, and contamination."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828491Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8316-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Dalton (1803) arranged known elements in order of atomic weights."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828497Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8316-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Newlands (1865) noticed that every eighth element, in order of atomic mass, repeated
  similar properties."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828503Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8316-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mendeleev swapped the order of atomic weights in order to fit elements better into
  groups of similar properties."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828509Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8316-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mendeleev’s periodic table had gaps and he predicted missing elements that were
  later found."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828516Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8316-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mendeleev was not aware of isotopes, so was unable to explain why the ordering by
  atomic weight was not always correct."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828522Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9686-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The prefixes milli-, micro-, nano-, and pico-, in this order, subdivide a metre into
  smaller and smaller divisions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828564Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9686-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Nanoparticles are 1-100 nm in size, and are larger than atoms and molecules."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828570Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9686-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The smaller a particle, the bigger its surface area to volume ratio."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828580Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9686-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Nanotubes are very small and extremely strong fibres that are thermal and electrical
  conductors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828586Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9686-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Nanoparticles have many applications; new applications for nanoparticulate materials
  are an important area of research."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828593Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9681-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In diamond each carbon atom is bonded to four others with strong covalent bonds to
  form a giant covalent structure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828599Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9681-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Diamond is very hard, has a very high melting point and does not conduct electricity
  (makes it good for cutting tools)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828605Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9681-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In graphite, each carbon atom is covalently bonded to three others to form layers of
  hexagonal rings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828611Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9681-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are only weak forces between the layers in graphite which can easily be rubbed
  apart (makes it a good lubricant)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828617Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9681-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Graphite conducts electricity because it has delocalised electrons which can move
  and carry charge/current."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.828627Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9644-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Paper, thin layer (TLC), and gas chromatography (GC) can all distinguish between
  pure and impure substances."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830028Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9644-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Chromatographic processes use a mobile and stationary phase. TLC and GC both use
  silica/alumina as a stationary phase."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830034Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9644-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Thin layer chromatography (TLC) uses locating agents to develop chromatograms and
  aid analysis of them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830040Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9644-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Chromatograms from gas chromatography (GC) also provide details about the amount of
  each component in a sample."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830050Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9644-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Retention factors (Rf) and retention times both provide quantitative information
  about a sample's components."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830063Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20083-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Atoms of many elements vary in the exact number of neutrons in their nucleus, and
  each version is called an isotope."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830103Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20083-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Existence of isotopes results in relative atomic masses of some elements not being
  whole numbers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830109Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20083-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Standard nuclear notation shows the chemical symbol, the mass number and the atomic
  number of the isotope."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830115Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20083-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The relative atomic mass is an average value that takes account of the abundance of
  the isotopes of the element."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830122Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9704-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The number of particles (atoms, ions, molecules etc.) in one mole of a substance is
  always the same."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830131Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9704-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mass of one mole of a substance is equal to the relative mass of the substance
  measured in grams."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830138Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9704-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mathematical relationships are manipulated to process practical results, calculating
  the number of moles in a substance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830144Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8374-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A catalyst affects the reaction rate without being used up."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830151Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8374-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A catalyst reduces the activation energy needed for a reaction."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830157Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8374-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """With a catalyst present, more collisions between reactants result in the formation
  of product(s)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830163Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8374-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Enzymes are biological catalysts."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830169Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8374-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Catalysts vary in efficiency; qualitative data helps evaluate effectiveness."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830175Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9702-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "'Potable' and 'pure' water are not the same material."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830185Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9702-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Water used in analysis must not contain any dissolved ions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830191Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9702-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The method used to obtain potable water depends on the water source."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830198Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9702-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Filtration and sterilisation are used to obtain potable water from groundwater and
  fresh water sources."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830204Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9702-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Desalination of sea water creates potable water by distillation or reverse
  osmosis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830210Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9683-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Graphene is a single layer of graphite, is very strong and conducts electricity."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830291Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9683-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Fullerenes are molecules of carbon with hollow shapes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830300Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9683-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The structure of fullerenes is based on hexagonal rings of carbon atoms, or on
  carbon rings of five or seven atoms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830308Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9683-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A Buckminsterfullerene is a spherical fullerene of sixty carbon atoms (C₆₀)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830314Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9683-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A carbon nanotube is a tube of graphene that is very long compared to its diameter
  and has a high tensile strength."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830320Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8440-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aluminium is above carbon in the reactivity series and can therefore not be
  extracted with carbon."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830327Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8440-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Impurities are removed from the bauxite ore at the start."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830333Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8440-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cryolite acts as a solvent and allows the electrolysis to take place at a lower
  temperature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830343Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8440-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carbon electrodes need to be continuously replaced as they react with oxygen as it
  is produced, forming carbon dioxide."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830349Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8440-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Electrolysis is an expensive process as it requires large amounts of energy."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830356Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9655-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are changes in arrangement, movement and energy of particles during state
  changes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830362Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9655-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are two types of change; physical and chemical, and the physical state of a
  substance can be predicted."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830369Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9655-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The attraction between particles has a role in determining the amount of energy
  needed for state changes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830375Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9655-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The particle model has limitations, for example by showing particles as same sized,
  inelastic spheres."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830381Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9655-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The model does not show the attraction between the particles which affects the
  amount of energy needed to change state."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.830390Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8323-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Chromatography has two phases, stationary and mobile, and separation depends on the
  distribution between these phases."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.831326Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8323-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Both aqueous and non-aqueous solvents can be used in chromatography."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.831332Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8323-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Chromatograms can be used to identify pure and impure substances."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.831338Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8352-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """metal + acid ⭢ salt + hydrogen; metal carbonate + acid → salt + water + carbon
  dioxide"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.831411Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8352-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The test for hydrogen gas is to introduce a lighted splint, which will make a
  squeaky pop in hydrogen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.831417Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8352-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The name of a salt formed is dependent on the acid used."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.831423Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8352-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """(s), (l), (g), (aq) in chemical equations identify the state of substances as solid,
  liquid, gas or in aqueous solution."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.831432Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8352-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carbon dioxide can be bubbled through limewater, which turns cloudy (test
  for CO₂)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.831438Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8394-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To make a product, raw materials need to be obtained and processed."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832096Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8394-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A life cycle assessment can reveal the people who benefit from each stage of a
  product’s life."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832102Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8394-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A life cycle assessment can reveal the costs to individuals or the environment at
  each stage of a product’s life."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832108Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8394-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At the end of its useful life a product can be repaired, recycled, incinerated or
  thrown away."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832114Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8394-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """LCAs are often subjective, so it is important to consider the vested interests of
  those reporting on their findings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832120Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27392-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fertilisers contain nitrogen, phosphorus and potassium compounds to promote plant
  growth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832126Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27392-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ammonia is a feedstock for manufacture of fertilisers, explosives, plastics, dyes
  and cleaning products."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832132Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27392-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Ammonia can be used to manufacture ammonium salts and nitric acid."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832138Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27392-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The laboratory preparation of ammonium salts is not the same as the industrial
  preparation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832146Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20360-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Heating sodium hydrogencarbonate in a crucible leads to its decomposition."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832268Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20360-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The risk involved with heating sodium hydrogencarbonate is low."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832277Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20360-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The stoichiometry for a reaction can be calculated given experimental data."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832283Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20360-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Because a gas is not a reactant in this reaction, the crucible lid remains closed
  throughout the heating process."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.832289Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9750-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are four ions present in a solution of brine: H⁺, OH⁻, Na⁺ and Cl⁻."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833590Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9750-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The product at the negative electrode is hydrogen gas."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833595Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9750-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The product at the positive electrode is chlorine gas."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833604Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9750-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Sodium hydroxide solution forms in the electrolyte solution, making it alkaline."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833610Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9750-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Two types of ions are in competition at each electrode."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833616Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8387-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Humans use Earth’s natural resources for most of our material needs."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833622Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8387-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Finite resources exist in limited quantities and will run out because we use them
  quicker than they can be regenerated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833627Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8387-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Synthetic products such as plastic and glass are made by humans using natural
  resources."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833633Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8387-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Sustainable development meets our needs without compromising the ability of future
  generations to meet their own needs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833639Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8387-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use of renewable resources, and the reuse and recycling of products, are sustainable
  development strategies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833644Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8344-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a giant ionic structure there are strong electrostatic forces in all directions
  between oppositely charged particles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833650Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8344-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ionic compounds have high melting points and high boiling points because strong
  ionic bonds need to be broken."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833656Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8344-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Most ionic substances can dissolve in water."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833662Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8344-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The ions of ionic compounds dissolved in water are free to move around and the
  solution can conduct electricity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833668Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8344-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The ions of ionic compounds that are in the liquid state are free to move around and
  the liquid can conduct electricity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833673Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20078-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The atmosphere comprises ~80% nitrogen and ~20% oxygen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833685Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20078-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The atmosphere contains small proportions of various other gases, including CO₂,
  water vapour and noble gases."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833690Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20078-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The atmosphere thins out with height which makes it harder for humans to breathe
  sufficient oxygen at high altitude."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833696Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20078-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The atmosphere contains water, mainly in its gas state but in its liquid (or solid)
  state in clouds and precipitation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833701Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20078-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The atmosphere also contains a wide range of solid particulates."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833710Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8364-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Combustion is the chemical combination of a substance with oxygen, involving the
  production of heat and light."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833716Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8364-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Complete combustion of fuels (like hydrocarbons) involve the production of carbon
  dioxide and water."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833721Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8364-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The chemical test for oxygen is a combustion reaction, involving relighting a
  glowing splint."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833727Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8364-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Incomplete combustion produces carbon particulates (soot) and carbon monoxide due to
  reduced oxygen levels."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833733Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20353-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Dalton (1803) arranged known elements in order of atomic weights."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833910Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20353-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Newlands (1865) noticed that every eighth element, in order of atomic mass, repeated
  similar properties."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833918Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20353-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mendeleev swapped the order of atomic weights in order to fit elements better into
  groups of similar properties."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833924Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20353-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mendeleev’s periodic table had gaps and he predicted missing elements that were
  later found."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833933Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20353-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mendeleev was not aware of isotopes, so was unable to explain why the ordering by
  atomic weight was not always correct."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833939Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8362-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A reaction profile compares the amount of energy the products of a reaction have
  compared to the reactants."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833971Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8362-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Exothermic chemical reactions transfer energy from reactants to the surroundings
  causing an increase in temperature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833977Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8362-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Endothermic chemical reactions transfer energy from the surroundings to the products
  causing a decrease in temperature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833983Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8362-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Activation energy is the minimum amount of energy transferred to reactants that
  allows a chemical reaction to start."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833988Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9638-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An experiment can be planned to measure the temperature change through continuous
  heating of a substance"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.833994Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9638-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Energy is needed to overcome forces of attraction between particles so temperature
  does not change when changing state"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.834000Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9638-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The change in state of pure substances can be seen on a heating/cooling curve as a
  horizontal line"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.834006Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9638-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There is a change of energy, arrangement, and organisation of particles of a pure
  substance at each stage"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.834014Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8397-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The atmosphere comprises 78% nitrogen, 21% oxygen, 1% argon and trace gases
  including 0.04% carbon dioxide."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.834020Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8397-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The atmosphere thins out with height which makes it harder for humans to breathe
  sufficient oxygen at high altitude."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.834026Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8397-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The atmosphere contains water, mainly in its gas state but in its liquid (or solid)
  state in clouds and precipitation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.834032Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8397-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The atmosphere also contains a wide range of solid particulates."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.834037Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8357-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Gently heating the acid speeds up the reaction, ensuring all acid reacts."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.834046Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8357-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The salt should be dried using an appropriate method (using filter paper, or in the
  oven)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.834052Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8357-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A pure sample should be prepared with equipment washed with distilled water to avoid
  contamination."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.834057Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8357-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Reacting a metal hydroxide with an acid also produces a salt and water."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.834063Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8357-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Reacting a metal carbonate with an acid can produce a desired salt with water, as
  well as carbon dioxide gas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.834069Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9730-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a reversible reaction the desired product needs to be continuously removed from
  the reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835067Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9730-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Natural gas is a feedstock for industrial production of ammonia."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835073Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9730-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Hydrogen, one of the raw materials in ammonia production, is produced from natural
  gas and steam."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835079Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9730-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In industry, the Haber process is typically performed at 150-300 atmospheres,
  400-450°C, with an iron catalyst."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835087Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9730-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ammonia production is energy-intensive and releases large amounts of carbon dioxide,
  contributing to global emissions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835093Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9646-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Distillation separates a soluble substance from its solvent based on differences in
  boiling points."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835119Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9646-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Distillation requires multiple pieces of apparatus which work in conjunction with
  each other."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835125Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9646-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The processes of boiling and condensing are involved in the process of
  distillation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835133Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9646-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Simple distillation is used primarily to separate mixtures of only two
  components."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835139Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8340-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Metals are good electrical conductors and good thermal conductors."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835148Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8340-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Metals can be stretched into wires, or bent/hammered into different shapes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835154Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8340-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Individual atoms do not have the physical properties of the substances that contain
  them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835161Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8340-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Metallic structures consist of positive ions and free–moving outer shell
  electrons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835166Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8340-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Electrostatic forces of attraction between ions and free electrons bind them all
  together in a giant metallic structure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835172Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20457-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The volume of one mole of any gas at room temperature and pressure (20℃ and 1
  atmosphere pressure) is 24 dm³."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835828Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20457-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Reacting mass calculations can use a combination of mass to volume calculations and
  vice versa."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835834Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20457-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Amount of substance (moles) can be calculated using multiple equations."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835839Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20457-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The choice of equation for calculating moles depends on the context of the problem
  or calculation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835845Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8426-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In an ideal chemical reaction, all atoms in the reactants would end up in useful
  products, with no waste."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835850Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8426-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The theoretical yield of a chemical reaction can be calculated from the reaction
  equation alone."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835858Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8426-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The percentage yield shows how actual yield compares with theoretical yield."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835864Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8426-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Atom economy is a measure of the efficiency with which a reaction uses its
  reactants."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835870Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8426-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Many factors will be considered when choosing a reaction pathway."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835875Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20082-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Atoms of many elements vary in the exact number of neutrons in their nucleus, and
  each version is called an isotope."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835880Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20082-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Existence of isotopes results in relative atomic masses of some elements not being
  whole numbers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835886Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20082-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Standard nuclear notation shows the chemical symbol, the mass number and the atomic
  number of the isotope."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835891Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28012-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A base is a substance that neutralises an acid to make salt and water only (this is
  a neutralisation reaction)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835912Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28012-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Hydroxides are generally soluble bases (they contain OH⁻ ions)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835921Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28012-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Metal oxides are bases that are generally insoluble."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835927Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28012-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Non-metal oxides are soluble and form acidic solutions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.835933Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9625-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Iron is alloyed with other metals to produce steel alloys."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.836999Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9625-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Copper is alloyed with other metals to make multiple useful alloys."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837007Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9625-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Gold, aluminium, and magnesium all form useful alloys with other metals."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837013Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8422-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fertilisers contain nitrogen, phosphorus and potassium compounds to promote plant
  growth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837019Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8422-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ammonia is a feedstock for manufacture of fertilisers, explosives, plastics, dyes
  and cleaning products."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837025Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8422-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Ammonia can be used to manufacture ammonium salts and nitric acid."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837030Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8422-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Phosphate rock is used in the production of fertilisers."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837035Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8422-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The laboratory preparation of ammonium salts is not the same as the industrial
  preparation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837041Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9635-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are changes in arrangement, movement and energy of particles during state
  changes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837072Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9635-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are two types of change, physical and chemical, and these can be explained in
  terms of the particle model."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837077Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9635-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The physical state of a substance can be predicted at specified temperatures."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837083Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9635-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Forces of attraction between particles have a role in determining the amount of
  energy needed for state changes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837088Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9666-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A base is a substance that neutralises an acid to make salt and water only (this is
  a neutralisation reaction)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837124Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9666-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Hydroxides are generally soluble bases (they contain OH⁻ ions)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837129Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9666-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Metal oxides are bases that are generally insoluble."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837137Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9666-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Non-metal oxides are soluble and form acidic solutions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.837144Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20369-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Group 1 elements are very reactive and their reactivity increases down the
  group."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.838652Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20369-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Moving down Group 1 elements, atomic mass, density and melting points increase."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.838657Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20369-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In chemical reactions, atoms of Group 1 elements lose one outer electron leaving
  full electron shells."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.838662Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20369-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Going down Group 1, the outer electron of each element is attracted to the atomic
  nucleus with less force."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.838668Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20369-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Group 1 metals react with water to produce alkaline solutions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.838673Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9658-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a chemical reaction, the atoms in reactants are rearranged and are the same atoms
  that are in the products."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.838694Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9658-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A theoretical yield is calculated using the stoichiometry of a balanced equation &
  relevant mathematical relationships."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.838699Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9658-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The number of moles of limiting reactant available is used to calculate the
  theoretical yield of a reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.838704Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9658-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If a reactant is added in excess, not all of it will react and some will be found in
  the final product mixture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.838709Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9658-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A limiting reactant is one that restricts the amount of product that can form from
  the available particles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.838715Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8398-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Early volcanic activity is thought to have made an atmosphere of carbon dioxide and
  nitrogen billions of years ago."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839326Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8398-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Carbon dioxide can dissolve in oceans and form carbonates that, over millions of
  years, can form sedimentary rock."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839333Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8398-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The amount of carbon dioxide was reduced by the formation of sedimentary rocks and
  photosynthesis by algae and plants."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839339Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8398-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Algae and plants produced the oxygen that is now in the atmosphere by
  photosynthesis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839344Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8398-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Phytoplankton in the oceans are responsible for roughly half of all oxygen
  production that takes place today."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839349Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8341-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In pure metals, ions are arranged in a regular structure with delocalised electrons
  between them"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839354Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8341-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If a metal is stretched or forced out of shape, its ions are able to move position
  without the metallic bonds breaking"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839359Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8341-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An alloy is a mixture of different metal elements or of metals with non metal
  elements (i.e. carbon)"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839367Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8341-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ions of different metal elements may be different sizes and have different
  electrical charges"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839372Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8341-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The structure of an alloy is not as regular as a pure metal and this affects its
  properties"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839377Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28152-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Data collected during a titration allows chemists to determine a solution’s unknown
  concentration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839382Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28152-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Concordant titres should be used when calculating a mean volume used to neutralise a
  solution."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839387Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28152-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The coefficients in a balanced equation indicate the stoichiometry (i.e. molar
  ratio) between substances in a reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839395Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28152-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The concentration of an unknown solution if found using the relationship:
  concentration = moles ÷ volume (in dm³)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.839400Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9711-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Hazard symbols provide vital safety information about chemical substances."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.840369Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9711-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Correct identification of hazard symbols is crucial for laboratory safety."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.840374Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9711-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Correctly choosing and using appropriate lab equipment is essential for conducting
  experiments safely and accurately."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.840379Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9711-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Risk assessments identify potential hazards & outline how to minimise risk; these
  can be general & specific precautions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.840387Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9711-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Safety protocols, like wearing eye protection and ensuring good ventilation, are
  essential when working with hazards."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.840393Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8417-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Corrosion is a general process of degradation of metals through various causes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841115Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8417-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Rusting is a specific type of corrosion, affecting iron in the presence of air and
  moisture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841120Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8417-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A metal oxide layer can protect the underlying metal if the oxide forms a physical
  barrier."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841125Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8417-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some coatings are reactive and contain a more reactive metal to provide sacrificial
  protection, e.g. zinc to galvanise."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841130Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8417-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Electroplating can be used to improve the appearance and/or the resistance to
  corrosion of metal objects."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841135Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9642-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Crystallisation is a technique that is used to separate a soluble solute from a
  solution."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841140Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9642-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Crystallisation involves the formation of a saturated solution and temperature
  differences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841146Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9642-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Crystallisation results in the loss of the solvent to the surroundings."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841154Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9665-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Equal amounts in moles of gases occupy the same volume under the same conditions of
  temperature and pressure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841160Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9665-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The volume of one mole of any gas at room temperature and pressure (20℃ and 1
  atmosphere pressure) is 24 dm³."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841167Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9665-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The volumes of gaseous reactants and products can be calculated from the balanced
  equation for the reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841173Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9665-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If moles of gas are known, its density can be calculated using molar gas volume and
  the relationship mass = RFM x moles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841178Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8886-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """One type of fuel cell contains hydrogen that reacts with oxygen from the air to
  produce a voltage."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841186Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8886-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Hydrogen used in fuel cells can be extracted from fossil fuels or produced by
  electrolysis powered by the National Grid."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841192Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8886-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Other fuel cells exist, but have other products than just water."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841197Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8886-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are many strengths and weaknesses of fuel cells, and these should be compared
  against other energy sources."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841202Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8319-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Group 1 elements are very reactive and their reactivity increases down the
  group."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841763Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8319-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Moving down Group 1 elements, atomic mass, density and melting points increase."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841768Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8319-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In chemical reactions, atoms of Group 1 elements lose one outer electron leaving
  full electron shells."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841773Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8319-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Going down Group 1, the outer electron of each element is attracted to the atomic
  nucleus with less force."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841778Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8319-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Group 1 metals react with water to produce alkaline solutions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.841783Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20138-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Chemical amounts are measured in moles (mol)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.842436Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20138-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """One mole of particles of a substance is defined as the Avogadro constant number of
  particles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.842441Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20138-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The number of particles (atoms, ions, molecules etc.) in one mole of a substance is
  always the same."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.842446Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20138-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use of Avogadro's number to calculate the number of particles of substance when
  number of moles is known and vice versa."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.842451Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20138-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mass of one mole of a monatomic element is equal to the relative atomic mass of
  that element measured in grams."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.842459Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9690-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The energy needed to break bonds and the energy released when bonds are formed can
  be calculated from bond energies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.843987Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9690-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The difference between the energy needed to break bonds and the energy released is
  the overall energy change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.843992Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20356-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a chemical reaction, the atoms in reactants are rearranged and are the same atoms
  that are in the products."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.843997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20356-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A theoretical yield is calculated using the stoichiometry of a balanced equation &
  relevant mathematical relationships."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.844002Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20356-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The number of moles of limiting reactant available is used to calculate the
  theoretical yield of a reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.844007Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20356-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If a reactant is added excess, not all of it will react and some will be found in
  the final product mixture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.844012Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20356-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A limiting reactant is one that restricts the amount of product that can form from
  the available particles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.844017Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8320-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Group 7 elements are very reactive and their reactivity decreases down the
  group."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.844660Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8320-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Moving down Group 7 elements, atomic mass, density, and melting and boiling points
  increase."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.844665Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8320-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In chemical reactions, atoms of Group 7 elements gain one outer electron making just
  full electron shells."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.844670Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8320-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Going down Group 7, the force attracting an extra electron reduces with the distance
  of each shell from the nucleus."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.844676Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8320-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Halogens are elements, halides are salts."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.844681Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20357-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Small masses of a substance, including magnesium, can be easily heated in a
  crucible."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.845706Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20357-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The crucible needs to be opened periodically to allow air (i.e. oxygen) to enter the
  apparatus."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.845711Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20357-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Lifting a crucible lid too often or for too long may lead to loss of product (i.e.
  lower final mass recorded)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.845716Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20357-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using practical data and conservation of mass, chemists can calculate unknown
  reactant masses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.845721Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20357-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Reactant masses can determine the empirical formula of a substance, including the
  ionic molar ratio of a metal & oxygen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.845729Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9621-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Atoms of many elements vary in the exact number of neutrons in their nucleus, and
  each version is called an isotope."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.845745Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9621-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Existence of isotopes results in relative atomic masses of some elements not being
  whole numbers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.845750Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9621-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Standard nuclear notation shows the chemical symbol, the mass number and the atomic
  number of the isotope."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.845755Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20153-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The number of particles (atoms, ions, molecules etc.) in one mole of a substance is
  always the same."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.845784Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20153-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mass of one mole of a substance is equal to the relative mass of the substance
  measured in grams."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.845789Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20153-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mathematical relationships are manipulated to process practical results, calculating
  the number of moles in a substance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.845794Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9663-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Small masses of a substance, including magnesium, can be easily heated in a
  crucible."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846708Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9663-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The crucible needs to be opened periodically to allow air (i.e. oxygen) to enter the
  apparatus."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846713Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9663-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Lifting a crucible lid too often or for too long may lead to loss of product (i.e.
  lower final mass recorded)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846718Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9663-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using practical data and conservation of mass, chemists can calculate unknown
  reactant masses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846728Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9663-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Reactant masses can determine the empirical formula of a substance, including the
  ionic ratio of a metal and oxygen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846734Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9676-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """pH is a logarithmic scale (as hydrogen ion concentration increases by a factor of
  10, the pH decreases by 1)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846739Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9676-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "For a given concentration, a stronger acid contains more H⁺ ions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846745Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9676-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Titration curves can be used to show the change in pH to allow chemists to pinpoint
  a more accurate end point."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846750Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9676-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A strong acid is completely ionised in aqueous solution, a weak acid only partially
  ionises."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846755Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9676-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Titration curves show how the pH changes throughout a neutralisation reaction."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846760Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28118-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Concentration of an aqueous solution is the mass of solute dissolved in 1 dm³ of
  distilled water, in g/dm³."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846765Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28118-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mass of one mole of solute is equal to the relative mass of the solute measured
  in grams."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846771Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28118-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Concentration can be expressed in g/dm³ or mol/dm³."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846776Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28118-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Equal volumes of solutions of the same concentration (in mol/dm³) have equal numbers
  of dissolved solute particles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846781Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28118-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Volume can be measured in various units; 1 dm³ is equivalent to 1000 cm³."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.846786Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8418-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Production processes for industrial materials are under continuous development, with
  new materials discovered."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.847821Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8418-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Several factors direct a choice of materials: performance, production processes,
  cost, aesthetics, and others."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.847826Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8418-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Composites are mixtures of materials made up of a matrix and a reinforcement."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.847831Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8418-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Qualitative data describes properties, while quantitative data measures properties
  numerically."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.847839Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9652-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Distillation can be used to purify water samples."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.848979Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9652-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Boiling point data can be analysed to assess the purity of water samples."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.848984Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9652-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The more impurities present in a sample, the larger the temperature range over which
  the water will boil."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.848989Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9652-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Pure water boils at 100°C."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.848994Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27389-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Transition metals are generally stronger, harder, more dense and have higher melting
  points than Group 1 metals."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.849365Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27389-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Transition metals react slowly with water or don’t react with it at all."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.849371Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27389-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Transition metals are often catalysts that speed up chemical reactions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.849376Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27389-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Transition metals can form ions with different charges and their compounds often
  exhibit vibrant colours."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.849381Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9746-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Balanced symbol equations can be written for the combustion of alcohols."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.849791Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9746-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It is difficult to measure directly the energy change of a reaction."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.849796Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9746-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Calorimetry can be used to measure a reaction's energy change indirectly."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.849801Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20676-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Group 7 elements are very reactive and their reactivity decreases down the
  group."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.851468Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20676-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Moving down Group 7 elements, atomic mass, density, and melting and boiling points
  increase."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.851474Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20676-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In chemical reactions, atoms of Group 7 elements gain one outer electron making just
  full electron shells."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.851479Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20676-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Going down Group 7, the force attracting an extra electron reduces with the distance
  of each shell from the nucleus."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.851486Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20676-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Halogens are elements, halides are salts."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.851492Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20361-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Equal amounts in moles of gases occupy the same volume under the same conditions of
  temperature and pressure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.852415Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20361-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The volume of one mole of any gas at room temperature and pressure (20℃ and 1
  atmosphere pressure) is 24 dm³."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.852420Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20361-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The volumes of gaseous reactants and products can be calculated from the balanced
  equation for the reaction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.852425Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20361-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If moles of gas are known, its density can be calculated using molar gas volume and
  the relationship mass = RFM x moles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.852430Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20458-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The volume of one mole of any gas at room temperature and pressure (20℃ and 1
  atmosphere pressure) is 24 dm³."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.853204Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20458-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Reacting mass calculations can use a combination of mass to volume calculations and
  vice versa."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.853209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20458-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Amount of substance (moles) can be calculated using multiple equations."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.853214Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20458-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The choice of equation for calculating moles depends on the context of the problem
  or calculation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.853222Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27391-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In an ideal chemical reaction, all atoms in the reactants would end up in useful
  products, with no waste."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.853227Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27391-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The theoretical yield of a chemical reaction can be calculated from the reaction
  equation alone."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.853232Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27391-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The percentage yield shows how actual yield compares with theoretical yield."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.853237Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27391-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Atom economy is a measure of the efficiency with which a reaction uses its
  reactants."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.853242Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27391-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Many factors will be considered when choosing a reaction pathway."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.853247Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20354-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Manipulating apparatus correctly ensures both accurate results and safety in the
  lab."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.856847Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20354-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Interconversion between units like grams, moles, volume, density & particles is
  fundamental in chemical calculations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.856852Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20354-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Successful interconversion is only possible if the units match."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.856860Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20354-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using the appropriate apparatus for a required measurement can help to reduce
  uncertainty."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.856865Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21042-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In phytomining, metal is extracted from a crop of plants that absorb metal ions
  through their roots."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.858902Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21042-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In bioleaching, metal is extracted from bacteria that extract metal from an ore."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.858907Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21042-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Electrolysis is a process used to separate metals from their compounds."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.858912Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-21042-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are advantages and disadvantages associated with each method of extracting
  metals."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.858917Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27913-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "An ionic equation represents the reaction between positive and negative ions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.861493Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27913-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The electric charge on each side of an ionic equation adds up to zero."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.861498Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-27913-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """(s), (l), (g) and (aq) in ionic equations identify the state of each substance as
  solid, liquid, gas or in solution"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.861503Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9661-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Empirical formula is the simplest whole number ratio of atoms of each element in a
  compound."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.862700Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9661-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using the masses of elements reacted together, or their percentage compositions,
  calculate the empirical formula."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.862705Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9661-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Knowing the relative formula mass of a substance, and its empirical formula,
  calculate the molecular formula."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.862710Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20137-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Group 0 elements are called noble gases (or inert gases) and are very unreactive
  with other elements."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.865566Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20137-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Group 0 elements can be described as having either full or empty outer electron
  shells."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.865571Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20137-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Noble gases emit coloured light when a high voltage is applied across them, and they
  do not decompose."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.865576Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20358-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The stoichiometry of a chemical reaction is the molar ratio of each substance in a
  balanced symbol equation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.868406Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20358-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Stoichiometric values can be calculated using masses found by experiment."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.868412Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20358-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Subscript values in chemical formula indicate the ratio of atoms/ions in a
  molecule/formula unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.868416Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20355-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Stoichiometry means ‘measuring elements’, from the Greek 'stoikhein' – meaning
  element and 'metron' – to measure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.868422Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20355-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Chemical equations should be interpreted in terms of moles (i.e. 1 mole of this
  reacts with 2 moles of that)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.868426Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20355-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mass of each reactant that does react can be worked out from the relative
  formula masses in the chemical equation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.868431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20355-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a chemical reaction, the atoms in reactants are rearranged and are the same atoms
  that are in the products."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.868436Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20355-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mass of products in a chemical reaction is equal to the mass of the
  reactants."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.868441Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8332-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a chemical reaction, the atoms in reactants are rearranged and are the same atoms
  that are in the products."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.868883Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8332-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mass of products in a chemical reaction is equal to the mass of the
  reactants."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.868888Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8332-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The sum of the RFM of the reactants equals the sum of the RFM of the products,
  taking account of balancing coefficients."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.868893Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28011-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Isotopes are atoms of the same element with different numbers of neutrons."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.870739Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28011-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Relative abundances of isotopes can be used to calculate the relative atomic mass
  (RAM) of an element."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.870744Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28011-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Mass spectrometry ionises samples to create positive ions for analysis."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.870749Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28011-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The M⁺ peak represents the molecular ion, indicating the molecular mass."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.870754Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-28011-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fragmentation in mass spectrometry helps identify molecular structure by breaking
  molecules into smaller ions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.870759Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20080-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The atomic number of an element states the number of protons in the nucleus of every
  atom of that element."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.877278Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20080-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The number of electrons in an atom is equal to the number of protons in the nucleus
  of the atom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.877283Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-20080-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The mass number of an element is about equal to the number of protons and neutrons
  in atoms of that element."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-09T00:46:37.877290Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

